Cell[TextData[{
 "Each step just prepends another 2 on the left. The \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]limit\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] is the infinite string \
...2222222 \[LongDash] all 2\[CloseCurlyQuote]s extending forever leftward. \n\
\nThis is -1.\n\nIf that feels like a trick, here is another one. We all know \
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SqrtBox["2"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "663218af-09d0-4952-bf0d-a337c148de27"],
 " is irrational \[LongDash] it cannot be written as a fraction, and it \
certainly is not an integer. But:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981585743770687*^9, 
  3.9815857982297697`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"be152f32-9bb4-48b3-9a58-\
478d587c1873"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Table", "[", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"k", ",", 
      RowBox[{"Mod", "[", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"-", "2"}], ",", 
        RowBox[{"7", "^", "k"}]}], "]"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"Mod", "[", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"Mod", "[", 
          RowBox[{
           RowBox[{"-", "2"}], ",", 
           RowBox[{"7", "^", "k"}]}], "]"}], "^", "2"}], ",", 
        RowBox[{"7", "^", "k"}]}], "]"}]}], "}"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"k", ",", "1", ",", "7"}], "}"}]}], "]"}], "//", 
  "TableForm"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981585810728085*^9, 3.981585810730023*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[36]:=",ExpressionUUID->"2a726521-59a9-4766-a020-15e83f09383d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 TagBox[GridBox[{
    {"1", "5", "4"},
    {"2", "47", "4"},
    {"3", "341", "4"},
    {"4", "2399", "4"},
    {"5", "16805", "4"},
    {"6", "117647", "4"},
    {"7", "823541", "4"}
   },
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}},
   GridBoxSpacings->{"Columns" -> {
       Offset[0.27999999999999997`], {
        Offset[2.0999999999999996`]}, 
       Offset[0.27999999999999997`]}, "Rows" -> {
       Offset[0.2], {
        Offset[0.4]}, 
       Offset[0.2]}}],
  Function[BoxForm`e$, 
   TableForm[BoxForm`e$]]]], "Output",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.98158581306824*^9},
 CellLabel->
  "Out[36]//TableForm=",ExpressionUUID->"d264af10-579c-4ff2-a6fa-\
b05653bd0f00"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The middle column is 5, 47, 341, 2399, ... \[LongDash] again exploding. But \
every single one of them, when squared, gives 2 (mod ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["7", "k"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "7c870023-c44a-4d9e-ae60-e9a1f1d1e59b"],
 "). These are successive approximations to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SqrtBox["2"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "6f641936-bfbe-4043-ab3f-0f7abaedc042"],
 ". Not in the reals, where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SqrtBox["2"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "b4a56a76-d420-4148-aeac-b6748354e400"],
 " lives between 1 and 2. In some other number system, where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SqrtBox["2"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "87b556cb-ad61-4c17-8222-070a716f6f5e"],
 " looks like an integer with infinitely many digits extending to the left.\n\
\nTwo questions should now be nagging:\n\n   1. In what sense are diverging \
integers \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]converging\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]?\n   2. Is \
this a curiosity, or is there real mathematics here?\n\nThe answer to the \
first question leads to p-adic numbers. The answer to the second is that \
these numbers underpin some of the deepest results in modern number theory \
\[LongDash] including the proof of Fermat\[CloseCurlyQuote]s Last Theorem."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981585890406507*^9, 3.981585944165718*^9}, {
  3.981586055511125*^9, 3.981586070817383*^9}, {3.9815861097030563`*^9, 
  3.981586118213634*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c23c6cc2-46e8-4c56-9e93-\
ed1da65b0a46"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Two Ways to Measure Distance", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.981586208151497*^9},ExpressionUUID->"0c82ada4-e80c-4dac-a160-\
84ebaff064f5"],

Cell["\<\
In the reals, two numbers are close when their difference is small: |47 - 5| \
= 42, which is not small, so 47 and 5 are far apart. End of story.

But there is another ruler. Instead of asking \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]how big \
is the difference?\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote], ask \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]how \
many times does 7 divide the difference?\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981586270978221*^9, 
  3.981586291464161*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"acad2fec-0956-4c6b-85ff-\
34e65f84e55b"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"diffs", "=", 
   RowBox[{"Table", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Module", "[", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"a", "=", 
          RowBox[{"Mod", "[", 
           RowBox[{
            RowBox[{"-", "2"}], ",", 
            RowBox[{"7", "^", "k"}]}], "]"}]}], ",", 
         RowBox[{"b", "=", 
          RowBox[{"Mod", "[", 
           RowBox[{
            RowBox[{"-", "2"}], ",", 
            RowBox[{"7", "^", 
             RowBox[{"(", 
              RowBox[{"k", "+", "1"}], ")"}]}]}], "]"}]}]}], "}"}], ",", 
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{"k", ",", "a", ",", "b", ",", 
         RowBox[{"b", "-", "a"}], ",", 
         RowBox[{"IntegerExponent", "[", 
          RowBox[{
           RowBox[{"b", "-", "a"}], ",", "7"}], "]"}], ",", 
         RowBox[{"N", "[", 
          RowBox[{"7", "^", 
           RowBox[{"-", 
            RowBox[{"IntegerExponent", "[", 
             RowBox[{
              RowBox[{"b", "-", "a"}], ",", "7"}], "]"}]}]}], "]"}]}], 
        "}"}]}], "]"}], ",", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"k", ",", "1", ",", "6"}], "}"}]}], "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{"Grid", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Prepend", "[", 
    RowBox[{"diffs", ",", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"\"\<k\>\"", ",", "\"\<a(k)\>\"", ",", "\"\<a(k+1)\>\"", 
       ",", "\"\<\[CapitalDelta]\>\"", ",", 
       RowBox[{"Subscript", "[", 
        RowBox[{"\"\<v\>\"", ",", "7"}], "]"}], ",", 
       RowBox[{"Subscript", "[", 
        RowBox[{"\"\<|\[CenterDot]|\>\"", ",", "7"}], "]"}]}], "}"}]}], "]"}],
    ",", 
   RowBox[{"Frame", "->", "All"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"Alignment", "->", "Center"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"Background", "->", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"None", ",", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"Blue", ",", "None"}], "}"}]}], "}"}]}]}], "]"}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981586310057373*^9, 3.9815863100596733`*^9}, {
  3.981586344281954*^9, 3.981586357612709*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[41]:=",ExpressionUUID->"2dcb4a43-f3e6-42b2-9622-a81149626948"],

Cell[BoxData[
 TagBox[GridBox[{
    {"\<\"k\"\>", "\<\"a(k)\"\>", "\<\"a(k+1)\"\>", "\<\"\[CapitalDelta]\"\>", 
     SubscriptBox["\<\"v\"\>", "7"], 
     SubscriptBox["\<\"|\[CenterDot]|\"\>", "7"]},
    {"1", "5", "47", "42", "1", "0.14285714285714285`"},
    {"2", "47", "341", "294", "2", "0.02040816326530612`"},
    {"3", "341", "2399", "2058", "3", "0.0029154518950437317`"},
    {"4", "2399", "16805", "14406", "4", "0.00041649312786339027`"},
    {"5", "16805", "117647", "100842", "5", "0.000059499018266198606`"},
    {"6", "117647", "823541", "705894", "6", "8.499859752314087`*^-6"}
   },
   AutoDelete->False,
   GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Center}}},
   GridBoxBackground->{"Columns" -> {{None}}, "Rows" -> {
       RGBColor[0, 0, 1], None}},
   GridBoxFrame->{"Columns" -> {{True}}, "Rows" -> {{True}}},
   GridBoxItemSize->{"Columns" -> {{Automatic}}, "Rows" -> {{Automatic}}}],
  "Grid"]], "Output",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.981586312445198*^9, {3.981586352500119*^9, 3.981586358038591*^9}},
 CellLabel->"Out[42]=",ExpressionUUID->"6a384dc8-849b-4d50-bffe-31946b6e9990"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The 7-adic absolute value of each successive difference is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     RowBox[{
     "\[LeftBracketingBar]", "\[CenterDot]", "\[RightBracketingBar]"}], "7"], 
    "=", 
    SuperscriptBox["7", 
     RowBox[{"(", 
      RowBox[{"-", "k"}], ")"}]]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "00da2463-001a-45f6-84a7-1366e19bae9e"],
 " , which is collapsing to zero. In this metric, 5, 47, 341, 2399, ... is a \
Cauchy sequence. It converges \[LongDash] just not in \
\[DoubleStruckCapitalR].\n\nThe rule is simple: two integers are p-adically \
close when their difference is divisible by a high power of p. The low digits \
(ones, p\[CloseCurlyQuote]s, p\[CloseCurlyQuote]s squared) are the important \
ones. The coefficient of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["p", "100"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "6fe66d4e-00b1-444e-97fc-d8334cb83576"],
 " is a tiny perturbation. This is the exact reverse of how we usually think \
about size."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981586412347308*^9, 3.9815864989461193`*^9}, {
  3.9815865391875677`*^9, 3.981586551588099*^9}, {3.9815865847067833`*^9, 
  3.981586643254642*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"afc801cc-eb4e-4fc5-b5e3-\
c251a0d244ce"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Expanding right, expanding left", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9813842023099127`*^9, 3.9813842241267*^9}, {
  3.981402718592387*^9, 3.981402745601761*^9}, {3.981586721953992*^9, 
  3.981586722755101*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"852a2886-b321-4340-9704-\
aee449e2c13f"],

Cell["\<\
In decimal, we approximate by expanding to the right:

    16/7 \[TildeTilde] 2.2 \[Rule] 2.28 \[Rule] 2.285 \[Rule] 2.2857 \[Rule] \
...

Each new digit is a smaller correction \[LongDash] a fraction of a power of \
10. We are summing negative powers of the base, and convergence means these \
corrections shrink to zero in the usual absolute value.

The examples above do the opposite: they expand to the left, adding higher \
positive powers of p. In the 3-adic world, -1 is the series

    2 + 2\[CenterDot]3 + 2\[CenterDot]3^2 + 2\[CenterDot]3^3 + ...

This diverges in \[DoubleStruckCapitalR]. But each partial sum is congruent \
to -1 modulo a higher power of 3, so the partial sums converge 3-adically. \
The same series, two different verdicts, depending on which ruler you use.

The digit tree makes this concrete. Each infinite path from root to boundary \
is a leftward digit expansion. The number -1 is the path that always chooses \
branch 2. The number -2 always chooses branch 1:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981586907832947*^9, 
  3.98158699332554*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"97034051-ddce-473a-9442-\
23c39d03582c"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Table", "[", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"k", ",", 
      RowBox[{"BaseForm", "[", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"Mod", "[", 
         RowBox[{
          RowBox[{"-", "2"}], ",", 
          RowBox[{"3", "^", "k"}]}], "]"}], ",", "3"}], "]"}]}], "}"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"k", ",", "1", ",", "8"}], "}"}]}], "]"}], "//", 
  "TableForm"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981587023960655*^9, 3.981587023963067*^9}},
