Cell["\<\
...111111 in base 3. Every negative integer corresponds to an eventually \
periodic path. Every positive integer is a finite path (it terminates in 0\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s). The p-adic integers contain all of \
\[DoubleStruckCapitalZ] \[LongDash] positive and negative \[LongDash] as \
infinite digit strings growing leftward.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981587076141313*^9, 
  3.981587090993206*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"23e2aad5-9f53-485b-abc3-\
fbf387308f27"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
 "There is no third option (",
 ButtonBox["Ostrowski's theorem",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ostrowski%27s_theorem"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ostrowski%27s_theorem"],
 ")"
}], "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9815871155915127`*^9, {3.981896294393263*^9, 
   3.981896294393532*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c909dfaa-98db-461b-a40e-\
8d720298a79b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "We have seen two ways to measure distance on the rationals: the usual \
absolute value and the p-adic one. Are there others?\n\nOstrowski\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s theorem says no. Every nontrivial absolute value on \
\[DoubleStruckCapitalQ] is equivalent to exactly one of:\n    \[Bullet] The \
usual absolute value |\[CenterDot]| \[Rule] completing \
\[DoubleStruckCapitalQ] gives \[DoubleStruckCapitalR]\n    \[Bullet] The \
p-adic absolute value ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", "\[CenterDot]", "\[RightBracketingBar]"}],
     "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b5162b81-dfc5-4613-aeb0-f0044c83ff85"],
 ", one for each prime p \[Rule] completing gives ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:211a", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d238829a-bed1-45da-887e-745afb8a73da"],
 " \n\nThe rationals sit inside both worlds simultaneously. Every question \
about \[DoubleStruckCapitalQ] can be studied from the real side, from the \
p-adic side for each prime, or \[LongDash] most powerfully \[LongDash] from \
all sides at once. This is the local-global philosophy that drives modern \
number theory: a problem over \[DoubleStruckCapitalQ] is equivalent to a \
family of problems, one over \[DoubleStruckCapitalR] and one over each ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:211a", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "38dae545-c1db-46af-9953-f30ae6159dc0"],
 "."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981587147166505*^9, 3.9815872093479147`*^9}, {
  3.981587246042028*^9, 3.9815872958236523`*^9}, {3.981896313036215*^9, 
  3.98189632123068*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"da35296d-72db-4937-98dd-\
b7d7c8aa16a9"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Two completions, two worlds", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.981587335595723*^9},ExpressionUUID->"8aa109bb-9956-4fa3-8b35-\
672c2c827e95"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Completing \[DoubleStruckCapitalQ] with the usual absolute value gives \
\[DoubleStruckCapitalR] \[LongDash] a connected continuum supporting \
classical calculus. Limits, derivatives, integrals: all built on the fact \
that nearby points can be connected by a continuous path.\n\nCompleting with \
the p-adic absolute value gives ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:211a", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "637d6a4b-4362-436c-8ab9-1fcf3e590c54"],
 " \[LongDash] a totally disconnected field. There are no arcs, no smooth \
paths between points. Every open ball is simultaneously closed, so the space \
shatters into clopen pieces at every scale. The topology is not a continuum \
but a fractal dust, homeomorphic to the Cantor set.\n\nThis means there is no \
continuum-dependent calculus: no usual derivative, no Riemann integral. And \
yet, as we will see, a rich form of harmonic analysis survives \[LongDash] \
not because of smoothness, but because the group structure and measure theory \
are enough."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9815873834742203`*^9, 
  3.981587448552466*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"337d2b8b-05da-464e-9220-\
d9369c42799d"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

