Cell[TextData[{
 "This image shows the 3-adic integers embedded as a rooted tree in the \
Poincar\[EAcute] disk. Each path from the center outward represents \
successive digits in a 3-adic expansion \[LongDash] at every node, the tree \
branches into three children. The three highlighted paths trace the \
expansions of \[Minus]1 (all blue, climbing toward the top \[LongDash] digit \
2 repeating forever), 1 (one green step then all red \[LongDash] digits 1, 0, \
0, ...), and 0 (all red \[LongDash] digit 0 repeating).\n\nThere is something \
unsettling about this picture.\n\nThe tree organizes itself into three \
sectors \[LongDash] each containing a perfect miniature copy of the whole. No \
digit is special. The structure is invariant under any permutation of {0, 1, \
2}, and the only rule is that all three must be present. This trifurcation \
repeats without limit, producing a self-similar branching that converges, in \
the infinite limit, not to a circle but to a fractal dust.\n\nThe faded \
sector coloring makes the topology visible. The red, blue, and green regions \
are the three cosets of 3\:2124\:2083 in \:2124\:2083 \[LongDash] the largest \
clopen balls. Within each sector, the sub-coloring shows the nine cosets of 9\
\:2124\:2083, and so on. The color boundaries are sharp, never gradual \
\[LongDash] every transition is a discontinuity. Moving along the boundary, \
the background color never fades smoothly from one hue to another; it jumps \
abruptly at every sector boundary, and within each sector it jumps again at \
every sub-sector. This self-similar discontinuity at every scale is the \
visual signature of total disconnectedness.\n\nThe ring of dots outside the \
tree is the Cantor boundary \[LongDash] the tree\[CloseCurlyQuote]s 729 \
deepest leaves projected radially onto a circle. Each dot is colored by its \
last digit, so the color alternates within each cluster: red-green-blue, \
red-green-blue, repeating at every scale. This speckled pattern breaks the \
illusion of continuity. From a distance the ring might look like a full \
circle. Look closer: the dots cluster in groups of three, and those groups \
cluster in groups of three, with gaps between every level. The faint guide \
circle shows where S\.b9 would be if the boundary were continuous. The dots \
do not cover it. They never will.\n\nThis is the decisive invariant: S\.b9 is \
connected, while ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[DoubleStruckCapitalZ]", "p"], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"e30222f3-856a-4d19-9bb6-fbe22de2bb10"],
 " is the opposite \[LongDash] every open ball is simultaneously closed, so \
the space shatters into clopen pieces at every resolution. In the p-adic \
metric, two numbers are close when they share a long initial prefix of \
digits, producing a tree-like ultrametric rather than the arc-length metric \
of a circle.\n\nThe three highlighted rays make this concrete. In the reals, \
0 sits \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]between\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] 1 and \
\[Minus]1: the distances are |1 \[Minus] 0| = 1, |\[Minus]1 \[Minus] 0| = 1, \
and |1 \[Minus] (\[Minus]1)| = 2 \[LongDash] an ordinary triangle with one \
side twice as long. In the 3-adics, all three diverge at the very first \
branch. Since 1 and \[Minus]1 already differ in their first digit, |1 \
\[Minus] (\[Minus]1)|\:2083 = |2|\:2083 = 1. All three pairwise distances are \
exactly 1: the triangle is equilateral. There is no \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]between.\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] The ultrametric \
inequality forces every triangle to be isosceles with the two longest sides \
equal, and here all three sides tie. This is a geometry where the number line \
has no meaning.\n\nCompleting \:211a with the usual absolute value gives \
\:211d \[LongDash] a connected continuum supporting classical calculus. \
Completing with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox[
    RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", "\[CenterDot]", "\[RightBracketingBar]"}],
     "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4f89726f-c6b3-45bf-811e-09a4bbf73dae"],
 " gives ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:211a", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "82f4f20e-560b-4800-9a6e-279514fba037"],
 " \[LongDash] a totally disconnected field where the familiar derivative and \
integral have no direct analogue. The geometry encoded in this tree is \
hierarchical and discrete at every resolution, which is precisely what makes \
p-adic analysis a different world from the real case.\n\nAnd yet.\n\nThis \
particular tree \[LongDash] the 3-adic one \[LongDash] has a visual resonance \
that extends far beyond number theory. Two thousand years before Hensel \
formalized p-adic numbers, Egyptian stonemasons carved the ",
 ButtonBox["papyrus capitals of the Temple of Horus at Edfu",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-egypt-upper-egypt-nile-valley-edfu-\
temple-dedicated-to-horus-god-composite-23723994.html?imageid=1C84FAE0-B25F-\
4185-A0B0-9A67C3310066&pn=1&searchId=6d409d85ab1d2455d2ded850dea8106d&\
searchtype=0"], None},
  ButtonNote->
   "https://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-egypt-upper-egypt-nile-valley-edfu-\
temple-dedicated-to-horus-god-composite-23723994.html?imageid=1C84FAE0-B25F-\
4185-A0B0-9A67C3310066&pn=1&searchId=6d409d85ab1d2455d2ded850dea8106d&\
searchtype=0"],
 ". The bundled stalks fan outward from a central column in a branching \
pattern that is, at least visually, the same recursive trifurcation: each \
cluster splits into sub-clusters, which split again, down to the individual \
fibers. \n\nThe carvers were not thinking about completions of \:211a. They \
were reproducing what papyrus looks like. But papyrus looks like that because \
its growth follows a branching rule \[LongDash] and branching rules with \
three-fold symmetry produce structures that are topologically identical \
whether they emerge from plant biology or from the arithmetic of primes.\n\n\
",
