V/NfpPik7E95kxqYeih1Li0yrTWdkB6ffkIgJ0gV9GSoZeRmDGYaZRZlDq9w
WLFzxbTQT9iQBWUty+oU0dGfqT6xvnijeCR7UXZN9tuciJzjubK5gty+PMO8
LXnjK71Wfr0Ks4qzqjtfI399/shq19W1a6A1CWu612qtLVw7ts573eH1pPWp
638oMC8oL3i1IXJDV6Fq4brC0Y3eG5uLpIqERbc3OW7avxmzmb+5f4vVlt1b
PhVzi6+UmJdUlnwo5ZRe+criq6qv5rYmbu0vsy3btw23TbDt1nbn7YfLZctX
lo/uCNjRXsGsKK54tTNu5+VK68r9u0i7xLuGq/yrOndr7962+0N1cvXNGrea
1j0qe7bsebOXu3don8u+lv2q+0v2vz/AP3Cn1ru2vU63rvIg7mD2wSf1EfW9
X7O+bmxQbihp+HhIcGj4cMjhnka7xsYmlaayZrhZ3Dx5JPbItW88vulsMWmp
bWW0lhwFR8VHn34b/+2tY37Huo+zjrd8p/PdnjZaW3E71J7XPt2R3DHcGd05
eGLxie4ux662702/P3RS42TNKflTZadJpwtPz51ZeWbmbObZqXNJ50a747rv
n486f6MnuKf/gt+FSxe9Lp7vde09c8np0snLDpdPXGFd6bhqe7W9z6av7Qeb
H9r6bfvbB+wGOq/ZX+saXDh4esh56Nx1j+sXb/jeuHpzyc3BW+G37tyOvT18
h3tn4m7a3Rf3su/N3l/3APug+KHMw8pHKo/qfjT4sXXYdvjUiMdI3+PQx/dH
OaPPfsr66cNY4RPqk8px9fHGCcuJk5Nek9eeLn069izz2exU0c+yP+95rv/8
u19cfumbjpoeeyF8Mfdr6Uull4deWb/qngmaefQ6/fXsm+K3Sm8Pv2O9630f
+X58NucD/kPVR4OPXZ/8Pj2YS5+b+w0AsgC3
       "], "RGB", "XYZ"], Interleaving -> True],
    Selectable->False],
   DefaultBaseStyle->"ImageGraphics",
   ImageSize->{605.2718749999985, Automatic},
   ImageSizeRaw->{1080., 781.},
   PlotRange->{{0, 1080.}, {0, 781.}}]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b44f979f-8647-48ba-af64-9bbf49d7c6a2"],
 "\n\nThat would be strange enough on its own. But there is a third echo, and \
this one is harder to dismiss.\nMeanwhile, in an entirely different corner of \
science...\n\nQuantum chromodynamics assigns to every quark one of three \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]color charges\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] \[LongDash] red, \
green, blue \[LongDash] governed by the gauge group SU(3). No color is \
privileged. The three labels are perfectly symmetric under permutation, and \
the only physical constraint is confinement: observable particles must be \
color-neutral, meaning the three charges sum to zero. In the 3-adics, 0 + 1 + \
2 = 3 \[Congruent] 0 mod 3 \[LongDash] the same neutrality condition, arrived \
at from entirely unrelated premises. The strong force does not know about \
p-adic numbers. The p-adic numbers do not know about quarks. And yet both \
demand exactly three symmetric labels whose sum vanishes.\n\nIt would be \
responsible to stop here and call this a coincidence of small numbers. Three \
is, after all, a small number. Many things come in threes.\n\nBut mathematics \
has a tradition of taking such coincidences seriously \[LongDash] sometimes \
decades before understanding them. Monstrous moonshine began as a \
numerological joke: the coefficients of the j-function, a modular form in \
number theory, matched the dimensions of representations of the Monster \
group, the largest sporadic simple group in algebra. The two objects had no \
business being related. It took McKay, Thompson, Conway, Norton, and \
eventually Borcherds (who won a Fields Medal for it) to discover that the \
connection was real, deep, and explained by vertex operator algebras and \
string theory.\n\nThe Langlands program began with similarly unexplained \
parallels between number theory and representation theory that \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]shouldn\[CloseCurlyQuote]t\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] \
have existed, and it has since become one of the organizing visions of modern \
mathematics. Not every coincidence is moonshine. Most are noise. But the ones \
that persist \[LongDash] the ones where the same structure keeps \
materializing in contexts that have no obvious communication channel between \
them \[LongDash] those are occasionally the first visible thread of something \
not yet understood.\n\nWe make no claims. We only observe that a 3-adic digit \
tree, the color charges of the strong nuclear force, and the papyrus columns \
of a temple built under Ptolemy III all seem to be telling the same visual \
story: three symmetric labels, recursive subdivision, self-similarity at \
every scale, and a sum that vanishes. None of them consulted the others. The \
tree does not know about the temple. The quarks do not know about the tree. \
And the stonemasons of Edfu, standing in the Nile Delta twenty-two centuries \
ago, certainly did not know about any of it.\n\nWhether they were all carving \
the same thing is a question we leave open."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.981499275161128*^9, {3.9815752961101837`*^9, 3.9815753982928457`*^9}, {
   3.981576075550757*^9, 3.981576087413418*^9}, {3.981576355114654*^9, 
   3.981576397906842*^9}, {3.981581141512931*^9, 3.981581220954627*^9}, {
   3.9815812758581953`*^9, 3.9815813014905033`*^9}, {3.981581358764798*^9, 
   3.981581436843842*^9}, {3.9815828896916637`*^9, 3.98158299326152*^9}, {
   3.981583093435485*^9, 3.981583095482602*^9}, {3.981583295631274*^9, 
   3.9815833201457767`*^9}, {3.981583638529131*^9, 3.9815836869186983`*^9}, {
   3.981583725135837*^9, 3.9815837293167353`*^9}, {3.981583785766198*^9, 
   3.9815837900303288`*^9}, {3.9815839866877193`*^9, 3.981584011217471*^9}, {
   3.981751618021751*^9, 3.981751782737352*^9}, {3.981752324963009*^9, 
   3.981752324963491*^9}, {3.981908292695443*^9, 3.981908293300332*^9}, {
   3.981908333029811*^9, 3.981908377927787*^9}, {3.9819084157238503`*^9, 
   3.9819084354183187`*^9}, {3.9819084672033863`*^9, 3.9819084772660418`*^9}, 
   3.981908699354287*^9, {3.9819087365789623`*^9, 3.981908798720819*^9}, {
   3.9819088345169477`*^9, 3.981908851705021*^9}, {3.9819088922423563`*^9, 
   3.981908904156798*^9}, {3.981908945392918*^9, 3.981908973646676*^9}, {
   3.981909011539734*^9, 3.9819090170543547`*^9}, {3.981909985694672*^9, 
   3.981910009249962*^9}, {3.981910052622596*^9, 3.981910055101309*^9}, {
   3.9819206657663794`*^9, 3.981920733016917*^9}, {3.9819209431208153`*^9, 
   3.9819209835737753`*^9}, {3.98192104877451*^9, 3.981921049857779*^9}, {
   3.9819211176387453`*^9, 3.9819211193374777`*^9}, {3.981921469467266*^9, 
   3.981921472700214*^9}, {3.981921660199316*^9, 3.981921660199863*^9}, {
   3.9819217830171347`*^9, 
   3.981921795627906*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f4977b34-a0e9-49c5-a6f7-\
2869fa058422"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The precise relationship: three levels of structure", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9819009051198463`*^9, 3.981900932419238*^9}, {
  3.981901127770678*^9, 
  3.9819011315378227`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"846c1cf7-8958-4892-8f7d-\
9212683816e5"],

Cell["\<\
The disk visualization raises a natural question: if the p-adics are not a \
circle, what exactly is the relationship? The answer has three layers, each \
more refined than the last.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981901161356347*^9, 3.981901166144868*^9}, 
   3.981901638119231*^9},ExpressionUUID->"baedee00-ad75-4488-9dea-\
1b0ef1063431"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Level 1: As sets \[LongDash] a bijection exists", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.9819011977741137`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"be9d2ca4-44c1-419b-af41-\
867dc09c8f3f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "As plain sets ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:2124", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "af54d72d-07b6-4068-beb6-02f0fb7f72af"],
 ", \[DoubleStruckCapitalR], and S\.b9 all have cardinality continuum. This \
is immediate: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:2124", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "206d6597-8341-4f0f-a6ec-ce8eedca63d8"],
 "= ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{" ", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"0", ",", "...", ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"p", "-", "1"}]}], "}"}], "\:2115"]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"190d04fa-30f6-4eec-8b4b-db68133bc35f"],
 " has the same cardinality as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{" ", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}], "\:2115"]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"c41caec2-a2bb-4ed8-b52b-28d06f102ca8"],
 "  = \[DoubleStruckCapitalR]. So a bijection f : ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:2124", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "ca1713cb-422e-42e4-9f5a-b08ebd6c8fe4"],
 " \[Rule] [0,1] certainly exists.\n\nBut a bare bijection says nothing about \
topology or metric. You can biject any two continuum-sized sets \[LongDash] \
including a line and a plane, or a circle and a Cantor set. The structure \
lives in which maps are continuous, not which maps exist."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9819012275011597`*^9, 3.9819012747525806`*^9}, {
  3.981901563214419*^9, 3.981901583687929*^9}, {3.9819019556190157`*^9, 
  3.981901957170882*^9}, {3.9819034759243193`*^9, 3.981903523335183*^9}, {
  3.981903578833679*^9, 
  3.981903620034917*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8bbeb198-b5b8-472f-a166-\
6f2b7adb50ec"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Level 2: As topological spaces \[LongDash] no homeomorphism", \
"Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.981901300180861*^9},ExpressionUUID->"092e923e-7dda-416c-9b30-\
6ad6cdb2171a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The obstruction is elementary. A homeomorphism must preserve connectedness, \
and:\n\n    \[Bullet] S\.b9 is connected (indeed, path-connected)\n    \
\[Bullet] ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:2124", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "ac846fdd-d98f-409a-9387-306bc91d9b07"],
 " is totally disconnected\n\nSo ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:2124", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5fd629d5-ea11-495c-8eda-4864f7aab221"],
 "\[NotTildeFullEqual] S\.b9 as topological spaces. Likewise, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:211a", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "650d5fad-5694-4e1d-b18c-cdb9b1b4376f"],
 " \[NotTildeFullEqual] \[DoubleStruckCapitalR], since ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:211a", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4723a019-b6e9-4134-99a2-21e97f7b2c54"],
 " is totally disconnected and \[DoubleStruckCapitalR] is connected. This is \
not a technicality. It means there is no continuous bijection in either \
direction that preserves the topology. The circle and the p-adics are \
fundamentally different shapes."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981901391592861*^9, 3.981901445945651*^9}, {
  3.9819015294333477`*^9, 3.981901533025642*^9}, {3.981901592134453*^9, 
  3.9819016031517963`*^9}, {3.981901792672517*^9, 3.9819017994897327`*^9}, {
  3.981901948068571*^9, 3.981901949155254*^9}, {3.9819019883729897`*^9, 
  3.981901996500821*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"195d1ad7-1c1d-4731-844a-\
527ecf3cd48e"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Level 3: As an embedded fractal boundary \[LongDash] yes, faithfully", \
"Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981901452208642*^9, 
  3.981901457711504*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3c37d635-4119-4a8b-9297-\
27f4ce1dc382"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "This is where the picture earns its mathematical honesty. Choose any \
integer B > p and define the embedding\n\n    \[CapitalPhi] : ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:2124", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5a1f7dcf-1204-4ef3-8fc8-a26d5be2cf61"],
 " \[Rule] S\.b9\n\nby sending x = (Subscript[a, 0], Subscript[a, 1], \
Subscript[a, 2], ...) to the angle\n\n    \[Theta](x) = 2\[Pi] \\!\\(\n\
\\*UnderoverscriptBox[\\(\[Sum]\\), \\(n = 0\\), \\(\[Infinity]\\)]\\(\n\
\\*FractionBox[\\(a\\_n\\), \nSuperscriptBox[\\(B\\), \\(n + 1\\)]]\\)\\)\n\n\
Because B > p, the digits {0, ..., p-1} never fill the full range {0, ..., \
B-1}, so the image Subscript[C, p,B] = \[CapitalPhi](",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:2124", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "eefdef97-538c-42c2-bc3e-432e2be3d039"],
 ") \[Subset] S\.b9 is a Cantor-like subset with gaps at every scale. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981901041887993*^9, 3.981901088177493*^9}, {
  3.9819016144820232`*^9, 3.981901615571114*^9}, {3.981901847151835*^9, 
  3.981901928686338*^9}, {3.981902009402356*^9, 3.98190206772324*^9}, {
  3.981903339988661*^9, 
  3.981903354248028*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f67068f2-d763-4b19-bfba-\
639e2187ca3c"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Why does this matter at all?", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9813842023099127`*^9, 3.9813842241267*^9}, {
  3.98138457668281*^9, 3.981384577040963*^9}, {3.981394456677741*^9, 
  3.981394461962604*^9}, {3.9814877267923737`*^9, 
  3.981487731273419*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e45af845-4f54-4440-ba06-\
049a1f99e735"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Number theory",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". The Hasse\[Dash]Minkowski theorem says a quadratic form has rational \
solutions if and only if it has solutions in \:211d and in ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:211a", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "f76a85bc-8610-470a-b9b8-75f81a09161b"],
 " for every prime p. The p-adics turn global arithmetic questions into local \
ones.\n\n",
 StyleBox["Physics",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". p-adic string theory and p-adic quantum mechanics explore ultrametric \
spaces as alternatives to the real continuum at Planck-scale distances, where \
the triangle inequality becomes the stronger ultrametric inequality: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"|", 
    RowBox[{"x", " ", "+", " ", "y"}], 
    SubscriptBox["|", "p"], 
    RowBox[{"\[LessEqual]", " ", 
     RowBox[{"max", "(", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"|", "x", 
        SubscriptBox["|", "p"]}], ",", 
       RowBox[{"|", " ", "y", 
        SubscriptBox["|", "p"]}]}], ")"}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"e341b598-c64d-4b9e-af53-cd96c2590696"],
 " .\n\n",
 StyleBox["Computation",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". Hensel\[CloseCurlyQuote]s lemma \[LongDash] the p-adic analogue of Newton\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s method \[LongDash] lifts solutions modulo p to solutions \
modulo p\.b2, p\.b3, etc. This is the backbone of algorithms in computer \
algebra.\n\n",
 StyleBox["Analysis",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". The p-adics are totally disconnected and yet locally compact \[LongDash] \
a topological structure radically different from \:211d. Doing calculus here \
forces you to rethink what continuity, integration, and differentiation \
really mean."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981394472799192*^9, 3.981394493342813*^9}, 
   3.981394722301045*^9, {3.9814058193813*^9, 3.981405841161126*^9}, {
   3.981411129872916*^9, 3.981411290407481*^9}, {3.9815845025566397`*^9, 
   3.98158450378363*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"b8cb9225-5cbd-4171-820b-\
553d7cb7abdc"]
}, Closed]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
 "Analysis in ultrametric ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[DoubleStruckCapitalQ]", "p"], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"0ca55b8b-d731-4f5f-9382-1e4d3b3d0198"],
 " space, discreet Fourier transform"
}], "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9813842023099127`*^9, 3.9813842241267*^9}, {
  3.98138457668281*^9, 3.981384577040963*^9}, {3.981394456677741*^9, 
  3.981394461962604*^9}, {3.9814877267923737`*^9, 3.981487731273419*^9}, {
  3.98158420528638*^9, 
  3.98158423421607*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"34ee90ca-a55c-47e0-91a6-\
5d519810dc22"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The Fourier transform on ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\:211a", "p"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "61d6bc81-3b1c-46cb-aa6e-ce80f91c66cc"],
 " exists not because of any notion of \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]smoothness\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] or \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]continuous oscillation,\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] but because the group structure and measure theory \
are sufficient. The \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]frequencies\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] aren\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]t sine waves \[LongDash] they\[CloseCurlyQuote]re \
characters that are locally constant and take only finitely many values on \
compact subsets. It\[CloseCurlyQuote]s harmonic analysis without harmonics in \
the classical sense."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981584490314671*^9, 3.9815845106402807`*^9}, {
  3.981640127248596*^9, 
  3.981640154198475*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"bb57866b-c384-4d44-8fec-\
75671cf271d8"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["What Dies", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981640161376642*^9, 3.981640166445557*^9}, {
  3.981640394782235*^9, 
  3.981640395151454*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6e5b0ffb-f7da-4aac-9309-\
f0dc359560ba"],

Cell["\<\
On \:211d, calculus rests on three pillars: Limits \[RightArrow] survive \
formally (\:211a\:209a is a complete metric space), but behave very \
differently. Sequences converge iff their terms go to zero in |\[CenterDot]|\
\:209a, which means the digits stabilize from the left. This is fine \
algebraically but geometrically it\[CloseCurlyQuote]s convergence \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]down the tree,\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] not along a \
line.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9816401435065002`*^9, 3.981640181980863*^9}, 
   3.981896773155552*^9},ExpressionUUID->"17f7cb0c-611c-49b2-a16f-\
e555c5376539"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"PadicDigitTree", "[", 
  RowBox[{"3", ",", "5", ",", 
   RowBox[{"RayDigits", "->", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"Padic", "[", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"-", "1"}], ",", "3"}], "]"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"Padic", "[", 
       RowBox[{"1", ",", "3"}], "]"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"Padic", "[", 
       RowBox[{"0", ",", "3"}], "]"}]}], "}"}]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"EdgeLabelMode", "->", "\"\<Ray\>\""}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"Layout", "->", "\"\<TopDown\>\""}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"SectorBackground", "->", "True"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"SectorBackgroundDepth", "->", "2"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"Background", "->", "None"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.981896639581143*^9, 3.9818966902868423`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[14]:=",ExpressionUUID->"679f3971-7c0e-493f-bf56-c60d774f1e82"],

Cell[BoxData[
 GraphicsBox[
  NamespaceBox["NetworkGraphics",
   DynamicModuleBox[{Typeset`graph = HoldComplete[
     Graph[{{}, {0}, {1}, {2}, {0, 0}, {0, 1}, {0, 2}, {1, 0}, {1, 1}, {1, 
