Cell["\<\
Derivatives \[RightArrow] the formal definition f\[CloseCurlyQuote](a) = \
lim(f(a+h)\[Minus]f(a))/h exists for certain functions, but it\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s almost useless. The problem: on a totally disconnected \
space, knowing f in a neighborhood of a tells you f on a clopen ball, but the \
function can do completely unrelated things on a neighboring ball at the same \
scale. The derivative doesn\[CloseCurlyQuote]t constrain global behavior. \
There are no differential equations worth writing down, because a local \
derivative can\[CloseCurlyQuote]t \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]propagate\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] information across a disconnected space.

The intermediate value theorem \[RightArrow] completely fails. Continuous \
functions on \:211a\:209a can jump between values without passing through \
intermediates, because there\[CloseCurlyQuote]s no connected path forcing \
them through.

So the entire edifice of classical analysis \[LongDash] ODEs, Taylor series \
as local-to-global tools, the idea that knowing a function \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]nearby\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] constrains it \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]far away\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] \[LongDash] collapses.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9816401435065002`*^9, 
  3.981640181980863*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"bde3f973-491e-4521-879b-\
6ed65bf35b18"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["What Survives", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9816402041143293`*^9, 3.981640210817237*^9}, {
  3.981640397537166*^9, 
  3.981640397930952*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"5b9160d9-fa5a-45ee-ba69-\
7a12c879fe82"],

Cell["\<\
Three things survive, and they\[CloseCurlyQuote]re enough:
1. Haar Measure (Integration)
\t\:211a\:209a is a locally compact abelian group, so it has a unique (up to \
normalization) translation-invariant measure. Integration works fine:
\[Integral]Qpf(x)\[ThinSpace]dx\\int_{\\mathbb{Q}_p} f(x) \\, dx\[Integral]Qp\
\:200b\:200bf(x)dx

is well-defined for integrable functions. The measure of a ball of radius p\
\:207f is just p\:207f. This is the one piece of \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]calculus\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] that transfers \
directly \[LongDash] you can integrate, compute volumes, define L\.b2 spaces. \
The reason it survives is that it\[CloseCurlyQuote]s algebraic (group \
structure), not topological (connectedness).\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.981640426263434*^9, 3.98165189133537*^9, {3.981820014254302*^9, 
   3.9818200236267548`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f1a51069-b0e0-441c-88ce-\
5f5ffdfd2193"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[{
 "Exact Rational \[DoubleStruckCapitalQ] Representation via Periodic P-adic \
Expansions in ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[DoubleStruckCapitalQ]", "p"], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"06392e6f-65d8-4fb5-b7ac-77a9f7ff24c0"]
}], "Chapter",
